      <div xml:id="NA82-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻiyiṟ puṇarccikkaṇ ṭaṉṉilaik koḷīiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how HE makes his stand during the union [with the help] of the confidante.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA82">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nōyu makiḻcciyum vīṭac ciṟanta</l>
<l>            vēyvaṉap puṟṟa tōḷai nīyē</l>
<l>            yeṉṉuḷ varutiyō naṉṉaṭaik koṭicci</l>
<l>            murukupuṇarn tiyaṉṟa vaḷḷi pōlaniṉ</l>
<l>            ṉuruvukkaṇ ṇeṟippa nōkkalāṟ ṟalaṉē </l>
<l>            pōkiya nākap pōkkaruṅ kavalaic</l>
<l>            ciṟukaṭ paṉṟip peruñciṉa voruttal</l>
<l>            cēṟā ṭirumpuṟa nīṟoṭu civaṇa</l>
<l>            veḷvacip paṭīiyar moytta vaḷpaḻīik</l>
<l>            kōṇāy koṇṭa koḷḷaik </l>
<l>            kāṉavar peyarkkuñ ciṟukuṭi yāṉē.</l>
        </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O you with a shoulder that had the beauty of bamboo,</l>
<l rend="indent2">excellent, while it is destroyed by pain and joy<note place="foot">Actually the variant <term xml:lang="ta">makiḻcci</term>, "joy", seems to make more motific sense: it is the alternation between HIS coming and not coming that destroys HER beauty. This literal paradox (that beauty might be destroyed by joy) might have induced a later scribe to exchange <term xml:lang="ta">makiḻcci</term> by <term xml:lang="ta">nekiḻcci</term>. Strange, however, is this address in the context of the poem, if we are prepared to take it with tradition as a poem addressed to a girl too young to understand the implication (in which case it might be preferable to read <term xml:lang="ta">nekiḻcci</term> and take the infinitive in another way: "so that pain and emaciation will be destroyed"). If we take it as an offer of marriage (which would be very rare in this poetry), it would be aptly addressed to a woman worn out by a phase of <term xml:lang="ta">kaḷavu</term>.</note>,</l>
<l>will you come to me, o creeper-woman of good gait?</l>
<l>I am unable to look [at you], while your beautiful eyes shine</l>
<l rend="indent">as [those] of Vaḷḷi who united with Murukaṉ [and] went [with him],</l>
<l>– to [my] little hamlet, where the forest people take away</l>
<l>the plunder taken by the killing dogs,</l>
<l rend="indent">having destroyed [their] lashes, that swarmed out<note place="foot">Actually, syntax is impossible here. We would expect it exactly the other way round: <term xml:lang="ta">moyttu vaḷpu aḻīiya</term>, absolutive followed by <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term>. What to do in these cases? We can only choose to emend the text or ignore the word order.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the greatly angered male of the small-eyed pig was caught in the</l>
<l rend="indent3">empty trap when bathing in the mud [and] going with dust on [its] dark back,</l>
<l rend="indent4">by the crossroad difficult to go, with large<note place="foot">Forms of <term xml:lang="ta">pōku-tal</term> in connection with plants are explained by T.V.G. as an expression of being tall-grown (see for example also Patiṟṟup. 13.14 <term xml:lang="ta">kār uṭai pōki</term>).</note> Nākam trees.</l>
        </lg>
